I want to design a local-first binary agent architecture that can index Solana data for free, derive oracle-grade trading signals, and run a self-auditing prediction engine that decides when to buy, sell, hold, or refuse action. The system should behave like a self-improving economic agent stack running on a local network, with each major function split into bounded components that can verify each other before any risky action is allowed.

The architecture starts with a Solana indexing layer that continuously ingests on-chain transactions, program events, account changes, DEX activity, liquidity movement, wallet clusters, volatility spikes, and timing patterns. That data should be normalized into a local analytics model and then passed into an oracle signal layer that produces structured market signals. Those signals should not directly trigger trading. Instead, they should flow into a prediction and strategy engine that evaluates at least 30 different prediction axioms such as momentum, liquidity stress, abnormal flow, price-discovery lag, coordinated wallet behavior, MEV risk, volatility compression, breakout probability, trend exhaustion, and confidence decay.

The architecture should be binary-driven in the sense that each agent stage can compile itself into an immutable local execution image, where the image becomes a reproducible terminal-runnable artifact. That image should be able to generate the correct Cargo crate structure, write the Rust source and `Cargo.toml` runtime specification, compile the binary, and expose a local API endpoint. The system should then open a second isolated local terminal or port as an anonymous gate to test the API from the outside, verifying that the compiled service is actually reachable and behaves correctly before it is trusted.

I need the architecture to include a crate-build loop where the agent can generate code, compile it, inspect warnings, decide whether warnings are safe to ignore or require repair, and then recompile. Warnings should not stop progress unless they imply real runtime or safety risk. The system should have an explicit warning-classification layer that determines whether a warning is cosmetic, optimization-related, correctness-related, network-risk-related, or severe enough to block the API runtime. Only warnings that threaten runtime correctness, security, or oracle integrity should stop the service from advancing.

Once the binary is running, I want a self-audit layer with around 40 checks that continuously inspect the compiled engine. These checks should validate API availability, endpoint correctness, Solana index freshness, signal integrity, prediction drift, strategy confidence, latency, memory pressure, unsafe trading conditions, external callback behavior, crate reproducibility, terminal execution health, local image immutability, and whether any risk calls are being made into the engine. If risk calls are detected, the system should flag them to the oracle layer and either degrade, isolate, or stop trading depending on severity.

The architecture should clearly separate the planes of the system: Solana ingestion, oracle signal generation, prediction axioms, trading decision logic, crate/image builder, local API runtime, test gateway, warning evaluator, self-audit system, and risk shutdown path. I also want local-network behavior made explicit: how services talk across local ports, how the anonymous gate probes the API, how callback verification works, how agent-built binaries are promoted or rejected, and how the system prevents a bad local build from being treated as a trusted oracle engine.

The final design should make clear how a self-driven agent can build itself, verify itself, expose a safe endpoint, audit itself continuously, and only then produce oracle-backed trading actions on Solana with bounded risk and strong local reproducibility.